This paper is about detecting domain generation algorithms (DGAs) used by malware, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper proposes a novel approach that combines context-sensitive word embeddings with a simple fully-connected classifier to perform classification of domains based on word-level information. This involves the use of deep learning architectures like convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and character-level long short-term memory networks (LSTMs), which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the pre-training of word embeddings on a large unrelated corpus, which is a common technique in natural language processing (cs.CL). Finally, the paper discusses the use of transfer learning to enable high-performing models with small training datasets, which is a technique commonly used in neural networks (cs.NE).
